<p>Social learning is implemented as follows. Each individual samples other members of the population at a fixed rate 
 <italic>κ</italic>. If ‘individual A’ samples ‘individual B’ and B’s strategy has a higher payoff that of A, then A will switch to B’s strategy with a probability proportional to the difference in payoffs. Thus if there are 
 <italic>x</italic> mitigators in the population, the rate at which a non-mitigator encounters a mitigator is 
 <italic>κx</italic>. Should there be a utility gain in switching (
 <italic>e</italic>
 <sub>
  <italic>M</italic>
 </sub> &gt; 
 <italic>e</italic>
 <sub>
  <italic>N</italic>
 </sub>), the non-mitigator will switch their strategy with a probability proportional to the payoff difference, 
 <italic>e</italic>
 <sub>
  <italic>M</italic>
 </sub> − 
 <italic>e</italic>
 <sub>
  <italic>N</italic>
 </sub>. Since there are a total of 1 − 
 <italic>x</italic> non-mitigators in the population, the total rate at which non-mitigators switch to being mitigators is 
 <disp-formula id="pcbi.1007000.e004">
  <alternatives>
   <graphic xlink:href="pcbi.1007000.e004.jpg" id="pcbi.1007000.e004g" mimetype="image" position="anchor" orientation="portrait" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/>
   <math id="M4">
    <mtable displaystyle="true">
     <mtr>
      <mtd columnalign="right">
       <mrow>
        <msub>
         <mi>r</mi>
         <mrow>
          <mi>N</mi>
          <mo>→</mo>
          <mi>M</mi>
         </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=</mo>
        <mi>κ</mi>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mrow>
         <mo>(</mo>
         <mn>1</mn>
         <mo>−</mo>
         <mi>x</mi>
         <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mspace width="2pt"/>
        <mtext>max</mtext>
        <mrow>
         <mo>{</mo>
         <msub>
          <mi>e</mi>
          <mi>M</mi>
         </msub>
         <mo>−</mo>
         <msub>
          <mi>e</mi>
          <mi>N</mi>
         </msub>
         <mo>,</mo>
         <mn>0</mn>
         <mo>}</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
       </mrow>
      </mtd>
     </mtr>
    </mtable>
   </math>
  </alternatives>
  <label>(3)</label>
 </disp-formula> Using similar arguments, one can show 
